1. Predicting Job Losses in the United States Coal Industry

All work (data collection, data cleaning, model creation, and prediction) done together by Javi and Priyanka

1.1 ABSTRACT

Central to decarbonization is the timely, well-planned phase out of coal production. Currently, coal accounts for roughly a third of global energy supply and contributes 45% of global CO2 emissions. The world’s decarbonization pathway is clear, especially in the energy sector. Promising renewable technology like wind and solar power are the cheapest sources of energy compared to coal in most major countries. A central question is how to make this transition just - the workers that have powered our economy are facing job loss, structural economic transition, and uncertainty around the future of their work. The transition to low-carbon, environmentally and socially sustainable economies can be a strong driver of job creation, social justice and poverty reduction, if properly managed with the engagement of governments, workers, and unions. This project explores part of this question by using capacity, addition, retirement data for solar and coal as well as levelized costs of energy and state demographic data to predict potential job losses and job gains in the coal and solar industries respectively. We utilized state level employment data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics and the National Solar Jobs Census, nameplate capacity, capacity additions, capacity retirements, and LCOE data from the Energy Information Administration as well as demographic data for each state from the American Community Survey. We tested OLS, Ridge, Lasso, as well as Decision Tree Regression Models to identify the best fit for each fuel source. Based on our test scores, the Ridge Model with an R2 of .91 was the best model for solar, and the Ridge model with an R2 of .88 was the best model for coal. Ultimately, all of the models performed relatively well (test scores around 90%) so we chose to fit the coal and the solar models based on what score was highest. Our results were inherently associated with high variance because each dataset was tailored to fit each model based on fuel source however we knew that this would be the case going into the project because our predictions were tailored to two different industries. We initially started off also hoping to create a model for wind, but ultimately could not find the data to build our dataframe.

1.2 PROJECT BACKGROUND

Central to decarbonization is the timely, well-planned phase out of coal production. Currently, coal accounts for roughly a third of global energy supply and contributes 45% of global CO2 emissions. The world’s decarbonization pathway is clear, especially in the energy sector. Promising renewable technology like wind and solar power are the cheapest sources of energy compared to coal in most major countries. Though the pace of this transition continues to fall behind net-zero targets, the clean energy transition seems inevitable, with renewable installation growth surpassing all projections. Coal industries across the world are financially insolvent, surviving only due to large subsidies by national governments, massive layoffs, and mechanization. The industry is associated with myriad community health, water pollution, and air pollution impacts, contributing to at least 800,000 premature deaths a year globally and many millions more illnesses. A central question is thus how to make this transition just - the workers that have powered our economy are facing job loss, structural economic transition, and uncertainty around the future of their work. The transition to low-carbon, environmentally and socially sustainable economies can be a strong driver of job creation, social justice and poverty eradication, if properly managed with the engagement of governments, workers, and unions.

Often coal communities that are most at risk of economic dislocation are geographically concentrated in a few parts of the country, with the coal industry a main economic activity and cultural identity for the community. Coal transitions in recent memory have seen significant drops in employment over a period of 10 years or less. However, transitioning thousands of employees into new employment cannot happen overnight. Thus, thoughtful planning and the proactive incorporation of opportunities of a renewable economy into a just transition are crucial to addresses fears of job loss and local economic decline. However, this also provides an opportunity to work creatively with communities to build new industries and employment opportunities. Moreover, it is increasingly clear that justice must be integral to the broader success of the climate movement. Without it, there can be no consensus between communities, sub-national, and national entities on the needed cooperation to mitigate and adapt to a climate changing world. This dynamic is evident at international negotiations like the UNFCC Conference of Parties, where developing and developed countries are often at a stalemate on climate cooperation because there is reticence from Western nations to shoulder historical responsibility and provide the funding needed for developing countries to successfully make the transitions away from fossil fuels.

In order to incorporate opportunities of a renewable economy, there must be reliable quantative analysis about the range of employment opportunities that are possible for countries and states through investment in growing the renewables industry. At the same time, there also must be proactive planning to draw down industries like coal, and in order to do so it is important to understand how many jobs exist in the industry, how many are going to be lost or gained and on what timescale. Understanding those trends, whether it be gains in renewables or losses in coal, can help support the interactions with communities to plan a just transition. It becomes very clear then what resources must be allocated to a region in order to re-skill workers, how much investment must be made in social safety nets to protect transitioning workers, and also identify the potential drivers of job growth in the renewables industry for that area.

Sources:

  2. https://endcoal.org/health/#:~:text=Coal%20is%20responsible%20for%20over,of%20coal%2Drelated%20air%20pollution.

1.3 PROJECT OBJECTIVE

The purpose of this project is to train and evaluate different prediction models to assess job losses and job gains by state in the coal and solar industry respectively. In order to do this, we built two separate models - one for coal and one for solar. Below will be further detailed descriptions about the coal data, data cleaning, and coal models in this notebook and we will also be submitting a separate report for our solar model. This question will answer a three-part resource allocation that was elaborated on in the project background: What is the timeframe of job loss for coal workers in the United States? What are the employment gains to be had from solar installations and how quickly is that industry growing in different regions? How many workers are affected by both transitions (towards solar and away from coal) and what implications does that have for resources allocated in terms of re-skilling, up-skilling, and broader economic diversification of a coal-dependent region?

In many cases the model shows that the areas most heavily invested in coal employment are often not as invested in solar but that is not always true and the model also provides a sense of which coal-dependent states are moving towards a solar industry vs ones that are lagging in their investment. In part it was incredibly challenging to build this model because we couldn't find any previous examples of people using predictive modeling to answer these types of economic questions around employment in different energy sectors.

In order to build this model, we focused on temporal prediction in order to enable prediction of coal job loss or solar job gains in each state by year. In order to do this, we had to use a timelag of 1 year - if our prediction year was 2013, our features were pulled from 2012 data, 2014 with 2013, and so on. Important to note here is that some of our features included forecasted capacity additions and retirements by fuel source and that data was also pulled from the same year as the features. In other words, forecasts made in 2012 about capacity changes in subsequent years (we set it to be 7 years out) were also factored into our 1 year future predictions for 2013. This was done for each subsequent year and while we were able to use historical data for most of the training and testing for our model from years 2013-2021, we also had to use forecasted data for some features in our 2022 prediction given that we didnt have historical values for features like income, population, and educational statistics by state. To do this forecasting, we used the forecasting tool in Excel which also ran a linear regression to predict forecasted values based on previous trends. We understand that this makes our results potentially less credible but we believe that it can still provide a rough estimate of the features that we need in order to predict our y-variable (jobs).

1.4 INPUT DATA DESCRIPTION

The data that we used to build our coal model included the following -

  • Bureau of Labor Statistics Data for historic employment (2012-2020) in the coal industry
  • Energy Information Data from 2012-2020 on nameplate capacity from the previous year, as well as projected capacity, additions and retirements by state from the previous year. In order to find this data we used the Annual Energy Outlook, the Short Term Energy Outlook, Electric Power Monthly, Electric Power Annual, reported out from the EIA-860 forms.
  • Lazard data on levelized costs of energy for coal from 2012-2021. We assumed a constant LCOE for each state based on the yearly value.
  • American Community Survey and Historic US Census Data for demographic features including median household income, resident population, population above 25 years, population with educational attainments reaching high school, population with educational attainments reaching an associates degree, and population with educational attainments reaching a bachelor's degree.

SGSTF of Data Listed Above:

  • Structure: For each of our individual data sets (which we merged into one dataframe) the data is grouped by state and fuel source. Each observation in the data frame corresponds to a year and a state, and each column represents either our response variable data or our feature variable data for that state in that year. We downloaded all of these files as Excel files.

  • Granularity: Each row represents an observation from a state in each year from 2012-2020.

  • Scope: For our geographic scope, our data covers all states of the United States except for Washington DC, Rhode Island and Vermont which we ultimately removed from our model building process because they had no data relevant to the model's ability to predict - there were no coal jobs in these states, nor any coal capacity, nor any projections for additions or retirements.

  • Temporality: Our data set covers the years between 2012-2020, and we predicted for the years 2021 and 2022. All predictions were done by state.

  • Faithfulness: Our demographic data comes from the Census Bureau, which is a government group that collects self-reported data on the population. Given that the data is self reported and voluntarily recorded, our data may be potentially skewed. Our BLS data comes from an annual mail survey of establishments that provides data on employment and wages by occupation and industry for over 800 occupations and for about 400 industries throughout the United States, and similar data for all states and selected metropolitan areas. Similar to the census data, there is potential for the data to be skewed because it is self reported and voluntarily recorded. However, the coal industry jobs data has a history of reporting to the BLS and seems reliable. In contrast, we couldn't use the solar and wind job data from BLS and had to turn to other sources (and exclude a wind model) because the jobs data was underreported for those sectors. Our Lazard data comes from historical averages and cross-validated with other LCOE estimates - little opportunities for data skewing. Finally, our EIA data came from multiple different datasets within the EIA database. Historic nameplate capacity data (for the previous year from our projection year) came from Electric Power Annual and our projected capacity additions and retirements came from the December version of Electric Power Monthly for years 2012-2020. For 2021 data (projecting 2022), we used the latest version of Electric Power Monthly which was released in October. We understand that this is an inconsistency in our data but unfortunately due to the fact that the December version has yet to be released yet, we had to rely on this data for our predictions. All of this data was originally downloaded catagorized by power plant (Form EIA-860) but we did some work in Excel first to sum the capacity, additions and retirements by state througn the use of a pivot table. This data is of course subject to change but because it is based on mandatory reporting at the power plant level, the data for the most part seems to be quite accurate in assessing coal capacity in the country.

1.5 and 1.6 - DATA CLEANING AND EDA

Our EDA is not in our coal and solar model files but can be found in a separate file which we plan to submit along with this readout. However, here we will detail our process by which we conducted our Data Cleaning Process and our EDA. We separated these two things from our model notebook because our Cleaning and EDA process was so lengthy and complex. In order to conduct the EDA, we worked in Google Collab because we initially thought it would be easier for the two of us to work on code at the same time. However, this was not the case and we ultimately worked on code together and then inputted into the Google Collab sheet. Before we could merge the data into one dataset, we first needed to clean and conduct an EDA on the four components of our data: Jobs, Nameplate Capacity, Additions + Retirements, and Demographic Data (population, income, educational attainment).

Before we discuss the EDA portion, I'll first outline the ways in which we had to clean our data prior to even importing into a Google Collab notebook. Because there were multiple datasets that we needed to collate for each variable and because each dataset had a different granularity and temporality of features, for example EIA data being catagorized by power plant and demographic data by state, we had to prep a lot of our datasets first in excel in order to get all variables defined by state and year. This included primarily collating yearly datasets into one large dataset and using pivot tables to sum up variables like namelpate capacity, historic addition and retirement as well as projected addition and retirement data by state and year (vs power plant). We also downloaded the full American Community Survey Census Data and created a new dataframe by pulling the specific columns that we wanted to include as demographic information for the years 2012-2020.

There are four components to our EDA file:

1. EDA Jobs 2. EDA Nameplate + Demographic 3. EDA Coal Ret & Add 4. EDA Solar Ret & Add (Not Relevant for Coal Model)

EDA Jobs: In this section of the EDA, we downloaded into the notebook the jobs data from 2012-2020 (all different excel spreadsheets coming from BLS). It was easy to manage this section because the datasets were essentially the same, only differing in their input values based on the year. First, we reorganized all the columns so each dataset was in the same order and had the same column names (initially some column names had capital letters and some didnt, or the column representing the same data had a different name depending on the year of the dataset). This was particularly straightforward to coal jobs because all coal jobs are classified under "Coal Mining" and we were able to pull the "total" column for each state for each year from 2012 to 2020.

EDA Nameplate and Demographic: In this section we imported the demographic data by state and year which we had pulled originally from the very large American Community Survey Dataset and pulled the specific columns that we wanted to use as demographic data - median household income, resident population, population over the age of 25, educational attainment levels for high school, associate degree and bachelors degree. In excel we had compiled all that data for each year and state and imported it into our notebook. Similarly, for nameplate capacity data we used the datasets from EIA and did a pivot table to get the summed nameplate capacity data by state and year (using the 8 different datasets). We then uploaded this into our notebook as well. and merged it with the dataframe from Step 1. The output of these steps is a coal dataframe including dataframe (coal and solar) with jobs, nameplate capacity and demographic information for each state, in each year from 2012 to 2020.

EDA Retirement and Additions: There are two parts to this section (one for coal and one for solar) but we will only focus on the coal retirements and additions for this part of the writeup. Solar will be addressed in the solar notebook. For historic retirement and additions (data for this was only a few values - there weren't many coal additions in the time period we were analyzing. Historic retirements and additions were first identified in excel and used a pivot table to sum up the retirements and additions by state and year. We then uploaded those files into our notebook and appended it onto the existing dataframe which at that point contained jobs, nameplate capacity, and demographic information. This was defined as "N Additions" and "N Retirements" where N represented the lagged year that we used to predict the subsequent year. For example, N additions and N retiremetns for the year 2013 were the additions and retirements for 2012. For Projected Retirements and Additions, we did a similar process first creating "N+1", "N+2"...until "N+7" columns for both additions and retirements. For clarity this meant that in the case of year 2013, "N+1" represented the projected additions or retirements made in 2012 for the year 2013. We did this for all subsequent years. In order to do this, we had to create a for loop that took our datasets from Excel which had totalled the projections by year and state and then the code was used to match to the state and prediction year in our larger dataframe.

At the end we added a column for our LCOE which was constant by state for each year. This dataset had already been copied and prepped previously in Excel so we just merged to our dataframe. The result was the final dataframe which we then used to build and train our model.

def fit_OLS(X,y):
    X_const = sm.add_constant(X)
    ols_model = sm.OLS(y,X_const)
    results = ols_model.fit()
    return results.summary()

from sklearn.model_selection import LeaveOneOut
loo = LeaveOneOut()
loo.get_n_splits(X)
y_tests = []
y_predictions = []

for train, test in loo.split(X): #a
    Xr_train, Xr_test = np.array(X)[train], np.array(X)[test] #b
    yr_train, yr_test = np.array(y)[train], np.array(y)[test] #c
    
    lr = LinearRegression()
    lr.fit(Xr_train, yr_train) 
    yr_pred = lr.predict(Xr_test) #d
    
    y_tests.append(yr_test[0][0]) #e
    y_predictions.append(yr_pred[0][0]) #e

r2_loo = r2_score(y_tests, y_predictions)
MSE_loo = np.exp(mean_squared_error(yr_test, yr_pred))
print("R^2 after LOOCV: ", r2_loo)
print("OLS MSE after LOOCV: ", np.exp(MSE_loo))

kf = KFold(n_splits = 4, shuffle = True, random_state = 1)

fold_mse = [] # initiate a list to hold the MSE associated with each fold

for t_index, v_index in kf.split(X):
    # Subset X and y into training and validation subsets
    X_fold_train = np.array(X)[t_index]
    y_fold_train = np.array(y)[t_index]
    X_fold_val = np.array(X)[v_index]
    y_fold_val = np.array(y)[v_index]
    # Initiate and fit a linear regression model using the training data
    lm = LinearRegression()
    lm.fit(X_fold_train, y_fold_train)
    # Predict the Y-values associated with the validation data
    y_pred = lm.predict(X_fold_val)
    
    # Find the testing MSE and append it to fold_mse
    MSE_F = mean_squared_error(y_fold_val, y_pred)
    fold_mse.append(MSE_F) 
    
print(fold_mse)

def fit_model(SKL_model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, alpha = 1):
    
        
        
    if SKL_model==LinearRegression():
        model != SKL_model()
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        model.coefficients = model.coef_
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    else:
        model = SKL_model(alpha)
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        model.coefficients = model.coef_
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
           
    
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    coef = model.coef_.flatten() 
    
    return mse, coef

Interpretation and Conclusions¶

Our results indicate that our feature variables have some predictive power to predict our response variables. It is important to first address the fact that set our y variable array was defined as the log of our response variables because many of our data inputs had 0s thus affecting our distribution (seen in the histogram above). Our data had many zeros in part because there weren't projections of capacity additions and retirements for every state and there also aren't coal jobs in every state thus affecting the distribution of our response variable. When getting our results for our predictions for job losses in the coal industry in 2021 and 2022, we had to first take the exponent of our values to cancel out the log but in doing so, some of our predicted values for jobs are exactly or around the value of 1 in states where there weren't any coal jobs as far back as 2014. This is because the log(0) is 1 and so when interpreting the results it is important to caveat our predictions by noting that job numbers equaling around 1 can be counted as zero. That being said, it is clear that there are a handful of states with a significant number of employees in the coal industry and that those jobs, according to our model, are declining quite rapidly in places like Pennsylvania and Kentucky. It was also interesting to see that some states didn't have coal jobs but had coal nameplate capacity - we believe this is due to the fact that some states have coal in their electricity generation portfolio but aren't necessarily producing coal in their state but rather importing it from other parts of the country.

Based on our model tests, as outlined above, we chose to conduct our predictions using a cross-validated Ridge model because the test score was highest when comparing all of the parametric models that we tested. Using the Ridge model, we are able to see that job losses in the coal industry are going to continue to happen at a rapid pace. As such, it is important now more than ever to allocate resources towards a just transition, with resources in particular to support transitioning workers out of the industry. Without that intentional allocation of resources, rapid job loss in the coal industry will only continue, creating economic dislocation for concentrated coal communities. We would recommend that policymakers at a state and federal level invest resources in these communities and also provide them with opportunities in either new energy industries (discussed further in the solar model) or broader opportunities for regional economic diversification. Currently, very few resources are allocated towards just transition policies in the United States but with our model, understanding the timeframe and rapidity of potential coal job loss, policymakers could begin to conduct proactive planning around supporting coal-dependent communities. We hope that readers will also care about our results, understanding that unfortunately the economics of the coal industry are ultimately not competitive with newer technologies.

Our results should be taken into account with a few caveats: first, our data was based on historical as well as forecasts for the future. While the EIA is a trusted source for these types of projections, some of the additions and retirements that are projected by the Agency are not necessarily guaranteed to be retired (or added). Second as discussed in the data sections above, our demographic data and BLS data is based on self-surveys which automatically means potential skewing of the data. Moreover, for our 2022 predictions we also had to use Excel forecasted values of demographics for 2021. However, all that being said our data does clearly have some significant relationship because all of our model testing had high validation scores across different types of models - OLS, Ridge and Lasso, and all of the tree models. Moreover, the model is not particularly externally valid because it is unclear whether the model could be applied to another scope or dataset. Our model also falls within the bias variance tradeoff by potentially having high variance. However, it is interesting to note that both our solar and coal models utilized a cross-validated Ridge model, potentially suggesting that our model does have some external validity when applied to other datasets using the same types of features.
